            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I've been looking at FreeBSD kernel source code for many hours and still cannot figure out why this is happening:\r\n- At PTY slave, the final output is successfully written to `t_outq` (`TIOCOUTQ` on PTY slave returns the number of written bytes that haven't been read yet).\r\n- When the last fd referring to PTY slave is closed, there should be a wait of at least 1 second for PTY master to read from `t_outq`. After that the remaining output is dropped. Indeed if I block the parent process for more than 1 second, the final output is always (instead of sometimes) lost.\r\n- And yet when reading from PTY master soon (about 1 ms) after child process exits, there is nothing to read from `t_outq` (`FIONREAD` and `read()` both return zero).\r\n- Holding a fd referring to PTY slave in the parent process makes the problem even worse (nothing to read from `t_outq` even when the slave fd is still being held).\r\n\r\nPerhaps the 1-second wait didn't happen or is cut short by a signal? Related:\r\n- https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd-src/commit/383f423be14a539990496fa9d9e818666234b1ec\r\n- https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd-src/commit/9750d9e5b6f011a99da26a6f1e57c65545d26473\r\n- https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd-src/commit/88d74d64d7ee5d01970fc47494d6da63ecf6cda7\r\n- https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd-src/commit/f64342e354d95a2e5101850ad6d9199c211748ad\r\n- https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd-src/commit/e046e8e680f4c507eee89402d95b761dee420909\r\n\r\nI'll keep the current solution for now.",
