            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I finally figured out the cause. It comes from the following two pieces of code in FreeBSD kernel in `devfs_close()` and `killjobc()` respectively:\r\n```c\r\n\t\t\t\tif (devfs_usecountl(vp) == 2 && !VN_IS_DOOMED(vp)) {\r\n\t\t\t\t\tp->p_session->s_ttyvp = NULL;\r\n\t\t\t\t\tp->p_session->s_ttydp = NULL;\r\n\t\t\t\t\toldvp = vp;\r\n\t\t\t\t}\r\n```\r\n```c\r\n\t\tif (ttyvp != NULL) {\r\n\t\t\tsx_xunlock(&proctree_lock);\r\n\t\t\tif (vn_lock(ttyvp, LK_EXCLUSIVE) == 0) {\r\n\t\t\t\tVOP_REVOKE(ttyvp, REVOKEALL);\r\n\t\t\t\tVOP_UNLOCK(ttyvp);\r\n\t\t\t}\r\n\t\t\tdevfs_ctty_unref(ttyvp);\r\n\t\t\tsx_xlock(&proctree_lock);\r\n\t\t}\r\n```\r\nWhen a session leader exits, `devfs_close()` removes the reference to the controlling TTY from the session only if no other process references the same TTY. Otherwise, `killjobc()` later revokes the controlling TTY referenced by the session, which causes remaining TTY output to be dropped.\r\n- For `shell-test` exiting immediately, the parent process may still be in the middle of `forkpty()` and holding the TTY fd. This is rare, but not impossible.\r\n- For Nvim TUI, the server process may still be holding the forwarded TTY fd. This is much more likely to happen than the `shell-test` case.\r\n\r\nTherefore, an alternative solution to using `tcdrain()` is giving up the controlling terminal by sending `TIOCNOTTY`, but that seems even stranger.\r\n\r\nSince the dropping of TTY output on revoke was introduced in <https://github.com/freebsd/freebsd-src/commit/88d74d64d7ee5d01970fc47494d6da63ecf6cda7>, this can likely be considered a FreeBSD kernel bug.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile #36792 seems to be a different problem.",
